029/**
030 * A palette of predefined colors as packed IPT floats, the kind {@link ColorTools} works with.
031 * You can access colors by their constant name, such as {@code OCEAN_BLUE}, by the {@link #NAMED} map using
032 * {@code NAMED.get("Ocean Blue", 0f)}, or by index in the FloatArray called {@link #LIST}. Note that to access a float
033 * color from NAMED, you need to give a default value if the name is not found; {@code 0f} is a good default because it
034 * will not occur in a valid IPT color. You can access the names in a specific order with {@link #NAMES} (which is
035 * alphabetical), {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE} (which is sorted by the hue of the matching color, from red to yellow to blue
036 * (with gray around here) to purple to red again), or {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS} (which is sorted by the intensity of
037 * the matching color, from darkest to lightest). Having a name lets you look up the matching color in {@link #NAMED}.
038 * <br>
039 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 10/13/2020.
040 */
041public class SimplePalette {
042    /**
043     * You can look up colors by name here; the names are lower-case, and the colors are packed floats in rgba format.
044     */
045    public static final ObjectFloatOrderedMap<String> NAMED = new ObjectFloatOrderedMap<>(60);
046    /**
047     * Stores alternative names for colors in {@link #NAMED}, like "grey" as an alias for {@link #GRAY} or "gold" as an
048     * alias for {@link #SAFFRON}. Currently, the list of aliases is as follows:
049     * <ul>
050     * <li>"grey" maps to {@link #GRAY},</li>
051     * <li>"gold" maps to {@link #SAFFRON},</li>
052     * <li>"puce" maps to {@link #MAUVE},</li>
053     * <li>"sand" maps to {@link #TAN},</li>
054     * <li>"skin" maps to {@link #PEACH},</li>
055     * <li>"coral" maps to {@link #SALMON},</li>
056     * <li>"azure" maps to {@link #SKY}, and</li>
057     * <li>"ocean" maps to {@link #TEAL}, and</li>
058     * <li>"sapphire" maps to {@link #COBALT}.</li>
059     * </ul>
060     * Note that these aliases are not duplicated in {@link #NAMES}, {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE}, or
061     * {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS}; they are primarily there so blind attempts to name a color might still work.
062     */
063    public static final ObjectFloatOrderedMap<String> ALIASES = new ObjectFloatOrderedMap<>(10);
064    /**
065     * Lists the packed float color values in this, in no particular order. Does not include duplicates from aliases.
066     */
067    public static final FloatList LIST = new FloatList(50);

688    /**
689     * All names for colors in this palette, sorted by lightness from black to white. You can fetch the
690     * corresponding packed float color by looking up a name in {@link #NAMED}.
691     */
692    public static final ObjectList<String> NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS = new ObjectList<>(NAMES);
693    static {
694        NAMES_BY_HUE.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
695            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
696                final float c1 = NAMED.get(o1), c2 = NAMED.get(o2);
697                final float s1 = saturation(c1), s2 = saturation(c2);
698                if(alphaInt(c1) < 128) return -10000;
699                else if(alphaInt(c2) < 128) return 10000;
700                if(s1 <= 0x1p-6f && s2 > 0x1p-6f)
701                    return -1000;
702                else if(s1 > 0x1p-6f && s2 <= 0x1p-6f)
703                    return 1000;
704                else if(s1 <= 0x1p-6f && s2 <= 0x1p-6f)
705                    return (int)Math.signum(intensity(c1) - intensity(c2));
706                else
707                    return 2 * (int)Math.signum(hue(c1) - hue(c2))
708                            + (int)Math.signum(intensity(c1) - intensity(c2));
709            }
710        });
711        for(String name : NAMES_BY_HUE) {
712            COLORS_BY_HUE.add(NAMED.get(name));
713        }
714        NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
715            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
716                return Float.compare(intensity(NAMED.get(o1)), intensity(NAMED.get(o2)));
717            }
718        });

723    /**
724     * Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed IPT_HQ float color.
725     * Color descriptions consist of one or more alphabetical words, separated by non-alphanumeric characters (typically
726     * spaces and/or hyphens, though the underscore is treated as a letter). Any word that is the name of a color in
727     * this palette will be looked up in {@link #NAMED} and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name
728     * words, the colors will be mixed using {@link FloatColors#unevenMix(float[], int, int)}, or if there is just one
729     * color name word, then the corresponding color will be used. A number can be present after a color name (separated
730     * by any non-alphanumeric character(s) other than the underscore); if so, it acts as a positive weight for that
731     * color name when mixed with other named colors. The recommended separator between a color name and its weight is
732     * the char {@code '^'}, but other punctuation like {@code ':'} is equally valid. You can also repeat a color name
733     * to increase its weight. You may use a decimal point in weights to make them floats.
734     * <br>
735     * The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the intensity of the described color; likewise, "rich" and
736     * "dull" change the saturation (how different the color is from grayscale). All of these adjectives can have "-er"
737     * or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. Technically, the chars appended to an
738     * adjective don't matter, only their count, so "lightaa" is the same as "lighter" and "richcat" is the same as
739     * "richest". There's an unofficial fourth level as well, used when any 4 characters are appended to an adjective
740     * (as in "darkmost"); it has four times the effect of the original adjective. There are also the adjectives
741     * "bright" (equivalent to "light rich"), "pale" ("light dull"), "deep" ("dark rich"), and "weak" ("dark dull").
742     * These can be amplified like the other four, except that "pale" goes to "paler", "palest", and then to
743     * "palemax" or (its equivalent) "palemost", where only the word length is checked. The case of adjectives doesn't
744     * matter here; they can be all-caps, all lower-case, or mixed-case without issues. The names of colors, however,
745     * are case-sensitive, because you can combine other named color palettes with the one here, and at least in one
746     * common situation (merging libGDX Colors with the palette here), the other palette uses all-caps names only.
747     * <br>
748     * If part of a color name or adjective is invalid, it is not considered; if the description is empty or fully
749     * invalid, this returns the float color {@code 0f}, or fully transparent black.
750     * <br>
751     * Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve",
752     * "lightest richer apricot-olive", "bright magenta", "palest cyan blue", "deep fern black", "weakmost celery",
753     * "red^3 orange", and "dark deep blue^7 cyan^3".
754     * <br>
755     * This overload always reads the whole String provided.
756     *
757     * @param description a color description, as a String matching the above format
758     * @return a packed IPT_HQ float color as described
759     */
760    public static float parseDescription(final String description) {
761        return parseDescription(description, 0, description.length());
762    }
763    /**
764     * Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed IPT_HQ float color.
765     * Color descriptions consist of one or more alphabetical words, separated by non-alphanumeric characters (typically
766     * spaces and/or hyphens, though the underscore is treated as a letter). Any word that is the name of a color in
767     * this palette will be looked up in {@link #NAMED} and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name
768     * words, the colors will be mixed using {@link FloatColors#unevenMix(float[], int, int)}, or if there is just one
769     * color name word, then the corresponding color will be used. A number can be present after a color name (separated
770     * by any non-alphanumeric character(s) other than the underscore); if so, it acts as a positive weight for that
771     * color name when mixed with other named colors. The recommended separator between a color name and its weight is
772     * the char {@code '^'}, but other punctuation like {@code ':'} is equally valid. You can also repeat a color name
773     * to increase its weight. You may use a decimal point in weights to make them floats.
774     * <br>
775     * The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the intensity of the described color; likewise, "rich" and
776     * "dull" change the saturation (how different the color is from grayscale). All of these adjectives can have "-er"
777     * or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. Technically, the chars appended to an
778     * adjective don't matter, only their count, so "lightaa" is the same as "lighter" and "richcat" is the same as
779     * "richest". There's an unofficial fourth level as well, used when any 4 characters are appended to an adjective
780     * (as in "darkmost"); it has four times the effect of the original adjective. There are also the adjectives
781     * "bright" (equivalent to "light rich"), "pale" ("light dull"), "deep" ("dark rich"), and "weak" ("dark dull").
782     * These can be amplified like the other four, except that "pale" goes to "paler", "palest", and then to
783     * "palemax" or (its equivalent) "palemost", where only the word length is checked. The case of adjectives doesn't
784     * matter here; they can be all-caps, all lower-case, or mixed-case without issues. The names of colors, however,
785     * are case-sensitive, because you can combine other named color palettes with the one here, and at least in one
786     * common situation (merging libGDX Colors with the palette here), the other palette uses all-caps names only.
787     * <br>
788     * If part of a color name or adjective is invalid, it is not considered; if the description is empty or fully
789     * invalid, this returns the float color {@code 0f}, or fully transparent black.
790     * <br>
791     * Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve",
792     * "lightest richer apricot-olive", "bright magenta", "palest cyan blue", "deep fern black", "weakmost celery",
793     * "red^3 orange", and "dark deep blue^7 cyan^3".
794     * <br>
795     * This overload lets you specify a
796     * starting index in {@code description} to read from and a maximum {@code length} to read before stopping. If
797     * {@code length} is negative, this reads the rest of {@code description} after {@code start}.
798     *
799     * @param description a color description, as a String matching the above format
800     * @param start the first character index of the description to read from
801     * @param length how much of description to attempt to parse; if negative, this parses until the end
802     * @return a packed IPT_HQ float color as described
803     */
804    public static float parseDescription(final String description, int start, int length) {
805        float intensity = 0f, saturation = 0f;
806        final String[] terms = description.substring(start,
807                        length < 0 ? description.length() - start : Math.min(description.length(), start + length))
808                .split("[^a-zA-Z0-9_.]+");
809        mixing.clear();
810        for (int i = 0; i < terms.length; i++) {
811            String term = terms[i];
812            if (term == null || term.isEmpty()) continue;
813            final int len = term.length();
814            switch (term.charAt(0)) {
815                case 'L':
816                case 'l':
817                    if (len > 2 && (term.charAt(2) == 'g' || term.charAt(2) == 'G')) { // light
818                        switch (len) {
819                            case 9:
820                                intensity += 0.150f;
821                            case 8:
822                                intensity += 0.150f;
823                            case 7:
824                                intensity += 0.150f;
825                            case 5:
826                                intensity += 0.150f;
827                                continue;
828                        }
829                    }
830                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
831                    break;
832                case 'B':
833                case 'b':
834                    if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'g' || term.charAt(3) == 'G')) { // bright
835                        switch (len) {
836                            case 10:
837                                intensity += 0.150f;
838                                saturation += 00.20000f;
839                            case 9:
840                                intensity += 0.150f;
841                                saturation += 00.2000f;
842                            case 8:
843                                intensity += 0.150f;
844                                saturation += 00.200f;
845                            case 6:
846                                intensity += 0.150f;
847                                saturation += 00.20f;
848                                continue;
849                        }
850                    }
851                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
852                    break;
853                case 'P':
854                case 'p':
855                    if (len > 2 && (term.charAt(2) == 'l' || term.charAt(2) == 'L')) { // pale
856                        switch (len) {
857                            case 8: // palemost
858                            case 7: // palerer
859                                intensity += 0.150f;
860                                saturation -= 00.20000f;
861                            case 6: // palest
862                                intensity += 0.150f;
863                                saturation -= 00.2000f;
864                            case 5: // paler
865                                intensity += 0.150f;
866                                saturation -= 00.200f;
867                            case 4: // pale
868                                intensity += 0.150f;
869                                saturation -= 00.20f;
870                                continue;
871                        }
872                    }
873                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
874                    break;
875                case 'W':
876                case 'w':
877                    if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'k' || term.charAt(3) == 'K')) { // weak
878                        switch (len) {
879                            case 8:
880                                intensity -= 0.150f;
881                                saturation -= 00.20000f;
882                            case 7:
883                                intensity -= 0.150f;
884                                saturation -= 00.2000f;
885                            case 6:
886                                intensity -= 0.150f;
887                                saturation -= 00.200f;
888                            case 4:
889                                intensity -= 0.150f;
890                                saturation -= 00.20f;
891                                continue;
892                        }
893                    }
894                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
895                    break;
896                case 'R':
897                case 'r':
898                    if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'i' || term.charAt(1) == 'I')) { // rich
899                        switch (len) {
900                            case 8:
901                                saturation += 00.20000f;
902                            case 7:
903                                saturation += 00.2000f;
904                            case 6:
905                                saturation += 00.200f;
906                            case 4:
907                                saturation += 00.20f;
908                                continue;
909                        }
910                    }
911                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
912                    break;
913                case 'D':
914                case 'd':
915                    if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'a' || term.charAt(1) == 'A')) { // dark
916                        switch (len) {
917                            case 8:
918                                intensity -= 0.150f;
919                            case 7:
920                                intensity -= 0.150f;
921                            case 6:
922                                intensity -= 0.150f;
923                            case 4:
924                                intensity -= 0.150f;
925                                continue;
926                        }
927                    } else if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'u' || term.charAt(1) == 'U')) { // dull
928                        switch (len) {
929                            case 8:
930                                saturation -= 00.20000f;
931                            case 7:
932                                saturation -= 00.2000f;
933                            case 6:
934                                saturation -= 00.200f;
935                            case 4:
936                                saturation -= 00.20f;
937                                continue;
938                        }
939                    } else if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'p' || term.charAt(3) == 'P')) { // deep
940                        switch (len) {
941                            case 8:
942                                intensity -= 0.150f;
943                                saturation += 00.20000f;
944                            case 7:
945                                intensity -= 0.150f;
946                                saturation += 00.2000f;
947                            case 6:
948                                intensity -= 0.150f;
949                                saturation += 00.200f;
950                            case 4:
951                                intensity -= 0.150f;
952                                saturation += 00.20f;
953                                continue;
954                        }
955                    }
956                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
957                    break;
958                case '0':
959                case '1':
960                case '2':
961                case '3':
962                case '4':
963                case '5':
964                case '6':
965                case '7':
966                case '8':
967                case '9':
968                    if(mixing.size() >= 2) {
969                        float num = 1;
970                        try {
971                            num = Float.parseFloat(term);
972                        } catch (NullPointerException | NumberFormatException ignored) {
973                        }
974                        mixing.set((mixing.size() & -2) - 1, num);
975                    }
976                    break;
977                default:
978                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
979                    break;
980            }
981        }
982        if(mixing.size() < 2) return 0f;
983
984        float result = unevenMix(mixing.items, 0, mixing.size());
985        if(result == 0f) return result;
986
987        if(intensity > 0) result = FloatColors.lerpFloatColorsBlended(result, WHITE, intensity);
988        else if(intensity < 0) result = FloatColors.lerpFloatColorsBlended(result, BLACK, -intensity);
989
990        if(saturation > 0) result = ColorTools.enrich(result, saturation);
991        else if(saturation < 0) result = ColorTools.dullen(result, -saturation);
992
993        return result;
994    }

1014    /**
1015     * Given a color as a packed IPT_HQ float, this finds the closest description it can to match the given color while
1016     * using at most {@code mixCount} colors to mix in. You should only use small numbers for mixCount, like 1 to 3;
1017     * this can take quite a while to run otherwise. This returns a String description that can be passed to
1018     * {@link #parseDescription(String)}. It is likely that this will use very contrasting colors if mixCount is 2 or
1019     * greater and the color to match is desaturated or brownish.
1020     * @param ipt_hq a packed IPT_HQ float color to attempt to match
1021     * @param mixCount how many color names this will use in the returned description
1022     * @return a description that can be fed to {@link #parseDescription(String)} to get a similar color
1023     */
1024    public static String bestMatch(final float ipt_hq, int mixCount) {
1025        mixCount = Math.max(1, mixCount);
1026        float bestDistance = Float.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
1027        final int paletteSize = namesByHue.size(), colorTries = (int)Math.pow(paletteSize, mixCount), totalTries = colorTries * 81;
1028        final float targetI = ColorTools.intensity(ipt_hq), targetP = ColorTools.protan(ipt_hq), targetT = ColorTools.tritan(ipt_hq);
1029        final String[] lightAdjectives = {"darkmost ", "darkest ", "darker ", "dark ", "", "light ", "lighter ", "lightest ", "lightmost "};
1030        final String[] satAdjectives = {"dullmost ", "dullest ", "duller ", "dull ", "", "rich ", "richer ", "richest ", "richmost "};
1031        mixing.clear();
1032        for (int i = 0; i < mixCount; i++) {
1033            mixing.add(colorsByHue.get(0));
1034        }
1035        int bestCode = 0;
1036        for (int c = 0; c < totalTries; c++) {
1037            for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; i++, e *= paletteSize) {
1038                mixing.set(i, colorsByHue.get((c / e) % paletteSize));
1039            }
1040            int idxI = ((c / colorTries) % 9 - 4), idxS = (c / (colorTries * 9) - 4);
1041            float intensity = idxI * 0.14f, saturation = idxS * 0.2f;
1042
1043            float result = FloatColors.mix(mixing.items, 0, mixCount);
1044            if(intensity > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, intensity);
1045            else if(intensity < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -intensity);
1046
1047            if(saturation > 0) result = ColorTools.enrich(result, saturation);
1048            else if(saturation < 0) result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(ColorTools.dullen(result, -saturation));
1049            else result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(result);
1050
1051            float dI = ColorTools.intensity(result) - targetI, dP = ColorTools.protan(result) - targetP, dT = ColorTools.tritan(result) - targetT;
1052            if(bestDistance > (bestDistance = Math.min(dI * dI * 3f + dP * dP + dT * dT, bestDistance)))
1053                bestCode = c;
1054        }
1055
1056        StringBuilder description = new StringBuilder(lightAdjectives[(bestCode / colorTries) % 9] + satAdjectives[bestCode / (colorTries * 9)]);
1057        for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; e *= paletteSize) {
1058            description.append(namesByHue.get((bestCode / e) % paletteSize));
1059            if(++i < mixCount)
1060                description.append(' ');
1061        }
1062        return description.toString();
1063    }
